description: Field Emission Microscope Wafer Inspection System    Resolution: 10nm at 1.0KeV over entire stage travel area at all tilt angles. Voltage range: 0.5KeV to 3.0KeV in 0.01KeV steps;3.0KeV to 5.0KeV in 0.1KeV steps.    Microcomputer control engineering workstation operates the system with user interface presented as a menu driven system. The preparation of job schedules, machine status, and location of the wafer can all be easily displayed on the CRT.    The electron optics system consists of a thermal field emission gun and electrostatic beam blanking and has been specifically designed for optimization at low KeV operation. Requires no water cooling and the final lense is finely pointed to permit tilting of 200mm wafers with no increase in the working distance. Beam blanked except when acquiring an image thereby reducing beam induced damage.    The scanning system operates at TV rates. The display of images is on a dedicated high resolution 14" color monitor with image processing and storage included.    The stage and wafer handling system is specifically designed to minimize particle additions to the wafers. the wafers are loaded individually into a prechamber from a standard 25 wafer carrier by a robot arm. They are aligned and the chamber is pumped down. The stage permit high tilt angles over the entire wafer surface with no loss of resolution or increase in working distance. The system consists of:    1. Computer controled 4-axis stage  2. Cassette loading and transfer of wafers into the system  3. X&Y travel: 200mm by 200mm for 200mm diameter wafers  4. Tilt: -15 to +60 degrees over the entire stage travel range with a 200mm wafer 5. Z axis: Fixed at all stage locations for all wafer sizes 6. Rotation: 360 degres endless, motor driven 7. Airlock chamber accepts up to 200mm wafers qith 1.5 minute pump-down time 8. wafer handling for 200mm wafers

title: NULL
description: Laboratory Mixing Extruder has the ability to extrude materials that vary widely in both physical form and polymer characteristics.  The material falls on to the hot smooth surface of the screw less cylindrical rotor. As the rotor turns, the material adheres to its surface and is subsequently forced against the inclined stationary surface of the scroll. As the rotor keeps turning the materials is conveyed towards the header containing the extruding orifice. While being conveyed, the material is collected in the radial gap and is pressured between the scroll surface and the header. The material is melted and enters the section between the end of the rotor and the inside surface of the header where it is rotationally sheared. This rotational shearing causes mixing and homogenization and the rotational shearing induces a centripetal pumping effect. This pumping transports the material radically inward and through the orifice to produce the product.  For additional info go to CSI-instruments.com

title: NULL
description: Gelbo Flex Tester. For testing of laminated plastics. Failure is determined by measuring the pinholes formed in a barrier structure after being subjected to the Gelbo flex test. Gelbo tester consists essentially of a 90mm diameter stationary mandrel and a 90mm diameter moveable mandrel spaced at a distance of 180mm apart from face to face at the starting position (that is maximum distance) of the full stroke.    The mandrels contain vents to prevent pressurisation of the samples. The motion of the moveable mandrel is controlled by a grooved shaft, to which it is attached.    The groove is designed to give a twisting motion of 440 in the first 90mm of the stroke of the moveable mandrel, followed by a straight horizontal motion of 65mm, so that at the closed position the mandrels are 25mm apart.    The motion of the Gelbo flex tester is reciprocal with a full cycle consisting of the forward and return strokes.    For the partial flex test cycle, the moveable mandrel is set up to travel only 80mm of the 180mm spacing.
